  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT275-kilavi">paruvavaraviṉkaṇ varavu nimittan tōṉṟa tōḻi talaimakaṭku uraittatu. </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">Told to HER by the confidante to whom a sign of [his]
          coming appeared at the coming of the season. </p>
      </div>

      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT275">
          <l> mullai yūrnta kalluyar pēṟik</l>
          <l> kaṇṭaṉam varukañ ceṉmō tōḻi</l>
          <l> yellūrc cērtaru mēṟuṭai yiṉattup</l>
          <l> pullār nallāṉ pūṇmaṇi kollō</l>
          <l> ceyviṉai muṭitta cemma luḷḷamoṭu</l>
          <l> valvi liḷaiyar pakkam pōṟṟa</l>
          <l> vīrmaṇaṟ kāṭṭāṟu varūun</l>
          <l> tērmaṇi kollāṇ ṭiyampiya vuḷavē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg xml:lang="en">
          <l>Come, <note place="foot">
              <term xml:lang="ta">ceṉmō</term>: here the imperative rather has the flavour of a
            particle of invitation (similar to Skt. hanta).</note> friend, let us come to see,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">climbing the stony height, crawled over by jasmine.</l>
          <l>[Is it] the bells worn by the good cows eating grass</l>
          <l rend="indent2">in a group with the bull coming to join <note place="foot">
              <term xml:lang="ta">cēr tarum</term> : here <term xml:lang="ta">taru</term> presumably
            in its auxiliary verb function of a process set in motion and continuing.</note> the
            village at night? <note place="foot">Or: "in the bright village", i.e. the village where
            the lamps/fires have been kindled (which might not be very bright, but brighter than the
            forest certainly).</note></l>
          <l>Is it the bells of the chariot sounding up there,</l>
          <l rend="indent">which comes on wild ways <note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kāṭṭu āṟu </term>
            might rather refer to a "forest river", which has a sand bank, for otherwise one has to
            explain why there are wet sands in the wilderness.</note> across the wet sand</l>
          <l rend="indent2">while attendants <note place="foot">
              <term xml:lang="ta">val vil iḷaiyar</term> : T.V.G. takes this as the usual reference
            to HIS entourage. Slightly problematic in this case is only the fact that there is no
            other noun which might refer to HIM, so one would have to take <term xml:lang="ta">cemmal
            uḷḷam </term> as a metonymy.</note> with strong bows protect the wings,</l>
          <l rend="indent3">with an exalted mind that completed the work to be done?</l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
  </text>
